<ArticleLayout
  title="How to Choose the Right Dog Bed for Your Home"
  description="Choose a dog bed by watching how the dog sleeps, measuring the resting position and planning for washing, climate and the floor space it will occupy."
  category="Pets"
  date="Updated July 2026"
  readingTime="9 minute read"
  image="/images/pet.webp"
  imageAlt="A calm pet-friendly living room with a washable dog bed near warm natural light"
>
  <p>
    A dog bed can be the right size on paper and still remain untouched. It may sit in an exposed
    walkway, feel too warm or force a dog that likes to stretch into a curled position. The animal
    notices those details even when the bed looks perfect in the room.
  </p>
  <p>
    Watch how and where the dog sleeps before comparing shapes or fabrics. Then measure the usable
    sleeping area, decide how the bed will be washed and mark its full footprint on the floor. The
    best bed is one the dog chooses and the household can maintain.
  </p>

  <h2>Let Sleeping Habits Lead the Choice</h2>
  <p>
    Observe the dog over several days. Curled sleepers may appreciate soft sides; dogs that sprawl
    usually need a generous flat surface. Some lean against furniture, burrow under a blanket or
    move between rooms as the temperature and household activity change.
  </p>
  <p>
    Location is part of that preference. A social dog may settle near people but outside the main
    traffic path. Another may seek a quiet corner. Moving an existing mat between two possible
    locations can reveal more than choosing a bed from a product photo.
  </p>

  <h2>Measure the Dog and the Usable Surface</h2>
  <p>
    Measure the dog in its usual resting position and allow room to change position. Product size
    names are not consistent, and outside dimensions can be misleading: thick bolsters may leave a
    much smaller sleeping surface than a plain rectangular bed with the same footprint.
  </p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Compare the internal sleeping length and width.</li>
    <li>Check how much space raised sides and backrests remove.</li>
    <li>Use the maker's weight guidance as an extra check, not a substitute for dimensions.</li>
    <li>Make sure the dog can get in, turn and lie down without hanging over an edge.</li>
    <li>Tape the outside dimensions on the intended floor before ordering.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Choose a Shape That Supports the Usual Posture</h2>
  <p>
    Flat mats are easy to move and can work in crates, laundries and cars. Bolster beds give some
    dogs an edge to lean against, but take up more floor space. Round or doughnut-style beds suit
    many curled sleepers and frustrate dogs that stretch out. Raised beds increase airflow and are
    easy to sweep under, although they feel less enclosed and may not suit a dog with limited
    mobility.
  </p>
  <p>
    “Orthopaedic” is not a guarantee of comfort or clinical benefit. Compare the actual thickness,
    firmness, construction and support under the dog's weight. If pain, arthritis, injury or a
    mobility change affects rest, ask the dog's veterinarian what matters for that individual.
  </p>

  <h2>Look Past Fabric Names to Everyday Wear</h2>
  <p>
    Plush fabric can feel cosy while holding hair, dust and grass seeds. Canvas-style covers may be
    easier to brush down but should not feel abrasive. Waterproof liners protect an insert, yet can
    add warmth or noise. Very soft loose fill may flatten quickly under a heavier dog.
  </p>
  <p>
    Check seams, zips and removable parts as carefully as the top fabric. No bed is indestructible.
    Torn covers, exposed filling and detached pieces should be removed from use, particularly with a
    dog that chews. Persistent destructive chewing calls for veterinary or qualified training advice,
    not simply a tougher-looking bed.
  </p>

  <h2>Make Washing Part of the Buying Decision</h2>
  <p>
    Dog bedding collects hair, drool, dust, mud and odour. A removable machine-washable cover helps
    only if it comes off without a wrestling match and fits the household washing machine. If the
    whole bed must be washed, check that it fits when dry and consider how heavy it will become when
    wet.
  </p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Confirm whether the cover, liner and insert have different care instructions.</li>
    <li>Check drying time, especially in humid or wet weather.</li>
    <li>Look for replacement covers if the insert is expected to last.</li>
    <li>Choose a surface that can be vacuumed or brushed between washes.</li>
    <li>Plan more frequent cleaning for beds near back doors or outdoor areas.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Our{" "}
    <a href="/guides/pet-cleaning-supplies-what-to-check-before-buying-cleaning-gear/">pet cleaning supplies guide</a>{" "}
    can help with the wider hair, mud and odour routine.
  </p>

  <h2>Match the Bed to the Life Stage</h2>
  <p>
    Puppies can toilet on bedding, chew it and outgrow it quickly. A simple washable option may be a
    better first purchase than a large premium bed chosen before adult size and sleep habits are
    clear. See{" "}
    <a href="/guides/new-puppy-essentials/">New Puppy Essentials</a>{" "}
    for the rest of the first-week setup.
  </p>
  <p>
    Older dogs often benefit from stable placement, low entry and a surface that does not slide as
    they step on or off. Avoid making assumptions based on age alone: some prefer firmer support,
    while pain or restricted movement may require specific veterinary advice.
  </p>
  <p>
    Dogs that run hot may choose a breathable mat or raised bed over deep plush sides. In cooler
    rooms, the same dog may seek a blanket. A bed that allows the household to adjust warmth is more
    versatile than one built around a single season.
  </p>

  <h2>Give the Bed a Restful Position</h2>
  <p>
    Keep the bed away from opening doors, cooking traffic and routes used at night. At the same time,
    avoid placing a social dog in an isolated laundry simply because the floor is easy to mop. The
    Australian RSPCA's{" "}
    <a href="https://kb.rspca.org.au/categories/companion-animals/dogs/caring-for-my-dog/can-you-give-me-some-advice-on-caring-for-my-dog" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">general dog-care guidance</a>{" "}
    calls for a clean, comfortable and safe environment that meets the dog's physical and mental
    needs.
  </p>
  <p>
    On tiles or timber, check whether the base slides, scratches or traps moisture. A separate
    non-slip layer should remain flat and dry. In a rental, also check for colour transfer from
    rubber backings and make sure the whole setup can be lifted for cleaning. The{" "}
    <a href="/guides/rental-friendly-pet-setup-what-to-check-before-buying-pet-gear/">rental-friendly pet setup guide</a>{" "}
    covers these floor-protection details.
  </p>
  <p>
    Where children share the home, the bed should give the dog a place to rest without constant
    interruption. Adults still need to supervise interactions and teach children to leave a resting
    dog alone.
  </p>

  <h2>Resolve the Trade-offs Before Buying</h2>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>A deep, soft bed may be warm and difficult to dry.</li>
    <li>A bolster offers an edge to lean on but reduces usable sleeping space.</li>
    <li>A raised design improves airflow but may be awkward for limited mobility.</li>
    <li>A very large bed supports sprawling but can obstruct a compact room.</li>
    <li>A decorative cover may demand more maintenance than the household will provide.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    There is no need to maximise every feature. Choose the combination that suits the dog's actual
    posture, the room and the cleaning routine. If the dog already sleeps happily on a washable mat,
    a new bed may not solve a problem.
  </p>

  <h2>Check the Bed in Context</h2>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Measure the dog at rest and compare the internal sleeping area.</li>
    <li>Mark the full bed footprint where it will sit.</li>
    <li>Confirm that covers and inserts can be washed and dried at home.</li>
    <li>Check grip, floor protection, seams, zips and loose filling.</li>
    <li>Allow for the dog's temperature preference, life stage and chewing habits.</li>
    <li>Seek veterinary advice for pain, allergy, skin or mobility concerns.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    The right dog bed does not have to be elaborate. It needs enough usable space, a position the
    dog accepts and a cleaning routine the household can sustain. Those practical details matter
    far more than how closely the cover matches the sofa.
  </p>

